               <p>A native of <placeName>Cornwall</placeName> (where <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> sheltered in his home in <date
                     when="1745">1745</date>), Maddern became an exhorter in <date when="1746"
                     >1746</date>, and a <seg ana="itinerancy">traveling preacher</seg> from <date
                     when="1747">1747</date>. In <date when="1751">1751</date> he married
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1345.xml"/>Molly Francis</persName>,
                  mistress of the girls&apos; school at Kingswood, and served as English master at
                  Kingswood <date from="1756" to="1757">1756–57</date>. The couple then moved to
                     <placeName>London</placeName>, where John became a respected local preacher. He
                  died by <date when="1770">1770</date>, and his wife returned to
                     <placeName>Bristol</placeName>, to serve as housekeeper at the New Room <date
                     from="1770" to="1782">1770–82</date>. See Atmore, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Memorial</hi>, 247; Ives, <hi rend="italic">Kingswood</hi>, 50; and Vickers,
                     <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 220.</p>
